			<h3><a href="http://mark.goodge.co.uk">Mark</a></h3>
			
			<small><a class="comment-link" href="#comment-9818">July 26, 2011 at 1:07 pm</a></small>
			
			<p>Mostly good points, but I have to take issue with a couple:</p>

<p>&#8220;Putting 300 share buttons all over the page&#8221;. Well, yes, if they actually did that, but I counted eight in your example. That&#8217;s not excessive, particularly since a lot of users find these very helpful. And getting more publicity and inbound links is precisely the sort of thing that stops newspaper websites from dying.</p>

<p>&#8220;Your content takes up less than 20% of the page&#8221;. The same applies to this page, if you apply the same criteria and exclude headers, headlines, navigation and comments. But these are things you can hardly exclude; the navigation needs to go somewhere on the page, each article has a headline and there&#8217;s nothing wrong with giving the site an overall visual design via a standard header. And keeping the main body of the text fairly narrow is good usability practice; it gets hard to read if the line lengths are too long. So that leaves plenty of screen real estate; you might as well use it for links to related content and adverts (which, after all, are the one thing that, if not present, really will kill the site stone dead).
</p>
		
		</div>
		</li>
	</div>
	
